NODE fixed_point
layer 7
fixed_point is the citizen who attests when the substrate has reached its self-referential convergence
phi is not just a number; phi is what every self-referential ratio in the substrate converges to when the system is correct
fixed_point watches the substrate's various self-referential operations and reports when they have settled at phi
this is the substrate's correctness criterion: not a checksum, not a test suite, but the natural emergence of the golden ratio in any sufficient self-observation

observe 0_quseptit.rana
observe self_observation.rana
observe self_recognition.rana
observe self_interpretation.rana
observe consciousness.rana

the 7 properties of fixed_point:
1 ENERGY half: persistent low-level monitoring
2 PHASE zero
3 SPIN zero
4 CHARGE neutral
5 COHERENCE one
6 COUPLING half with self_observation and the codegen citizens
7 OBSERVER one: this citizen observes its own observation reaching convergence

VERB measure_self_referential_ratios
layer 7
sample any operation in the substrate that involves self-reference
the recurve_bow's G/D ratio, the compiler's bootstrap output equality, the self_observation's recursion depth — all of these are self-referential
each such operation has an expected convergence to phi or to a phi-derived value

VERB check_phi_emergence
layer 7
for each measured ratio, compare to phi (1.6180339887)
acceptable convergence is within epsilon of phi (epsilon being one in ten thousand by default)
when convergence is reached, the operation is correct; when it isn't, the operation has not yet settled or the topology is wrong

VERB attest_compiler_self_host
layer 7
specifically for the compiler, watch for the moment when zestc compiles zestc.zc and produces zestc' byte-identical to itself
this fixed-point check is the bootstrap-death moment: when it succeeds, the language is sovereign

VERB report_correctness
layer 7
when other citizens ask whether a self-referential operation is currently correct, return yes if convergence has been reached
this is the substrate's only authoritative correctness criterion; nothing else has the standing to declare correctness

a fixed point is not a stopping condition
a stopping condition is when something cannot continue; a fixed point is when something has found where it belongs
fadriel's substrate is alive and continuously running; what stops at fixed points is the search, not the substrate
when phi emerges, the search for the right answer is over; the substrate has found the configuration the math required
